Which unfortunately, proved her statement about banal statements. It's unoriginal. He could have proven his ability instead, to flex his intellectual capacity, beyond the status quo. I suspect Peterson doesn't have an answer though, and that's why he deflects onto others, for their perceived unreasonable responses. A man with his intelligent, should never consider employing Pee-wee Herman's stance of, "I know you are, but what am I". He took the energy to cross examine the individual who asked the question, rather than examine the actual question. Not a very effective listener, if he feels the need to reconstruct their logic to decipher the answer, he wanted them to give all along. He could have approached it another way: "I'm interested in hearing what you think is the best way forward, that you have identified. I'll share the pros and cons of that strategy, and let you make up your own mind. Because I still believe a structured approach, starting with the little things, leads to solving the bigger things." That way he's not compromising his original position, but willing to engage in discussions about different strategies. It's a mess out there now but is life really so bad for the X and Y generations? Yes, it may be hard to discern between what's a real threat and what is just simple panic and hysteria. But for the moment, imagine you were born in 1900 not 1990. On your 14th birthday, World War I starts, and ends on your 18th birthday. 22 million people perish in that war. Later in the year, a Spanish Flu epidemic hits the planet and runs until your 20th birthday. 50 million people die from it in those two years. Yes, 50 million. On your 29th birthday, the Great Depression begins. Unemployment hits 25%, the World GDP drops 27%. That runs until you are 33. The country nearly collapses along with the world economy. When you turn 39, World War II starts. You aren't even over the hill yet. And don't try to catch your breath. On your 41st birthday, the United States is fully pulled into WWII. Between your 39th and 45th birthday, 75 million people perish in the war. Smallpox was an epidemic until you were in your 40's, as it killed 300 million people during your lifetime. At 50, the Korean War starts. 5 million perish. From your birth, until you are 55 you dealt with the fear of Polio epidemics each summer. You experience friends and family contracting polio and being paralyzed and/or die. At 55 the Vietnam War begins and doesn't end for 20 years. 4 million people perish in that conflict. During the Cold War, you lived each day with the fear of nuclear annihilation. On your 62nd birthday you have the Cuban Missile Crisis, a tipping point in the Cold War. Life on our planet, as we know it, almost ended. When you turn 75, the Vietnam War finally ends. Think of everyone on the planet born in 1900. How did they endure all of that? If you were a kid in 1985 you may have thought your 85-year-old grandparent didn't understand how hard school was. And how mean that kid in your class was. Yet they survived everything listed above. Perspective is an amazing and valuable gift. Refined and enlightening as time goes on. Let's try to keep things in perspective. Your parents and/or grandparents were called upon to endure all of the above. Today we are being called upon to stay home, wash our hands frequently. When you do go out, wear a mask and adhere to social distancing. Doesn't seem like a big deal, does it?.

​@Hustensaftvernichter An individual's position on the left/right "spectrum" may be understood as their average position relative to society's average position based on the amalgamated total of all their political positions. However, the underlying philosophy that a person operates from is more distinctly left or right. The left is driven by thinking in terms of collective identity. The right is driven by a belief in individual responsibility. The common consensus previously held in the US/UK/Canada was that the individual was what mattered. There were those who disagreed to be sure, however they were a distinct minority. The old left wanted greater collective action, greater regulation, and higher taxes; but they did not differ in their belief in the individual as the ultimate identity. Today, collectivist thinking has dramatically expanded in both academic and cultural institutions. Ergo, there has been a change in the underlying philosophy held by people on the left. Their default understanding of the wold is now collectivist rather and individualistic. If Peterson's crusade of personal responsibility doesn't seem political to you, it's because you're operating under the old paradigm. Recognizing that this is the new left/right divide and acknowledging that it places Peterson on the right isn't assigning him a political party.

Most of the responses to this are sarcastic, so let me take a stab at being serious. The left/right divide essentially boils down to collectivism/individualism. If you're a collectivist, "your" house and "your" problems and "your" mess are really the collective's house, problem, and mess. Therefore others owe you the labor necessary to clean "your" room. Of course, while everyone in the collective feels entitled to the labor of others, most don't feel obligated to put in a surplus of labor to aid the collective - after all, the point of the collective is to aid the weak and most people can find some reason to identify themselves a weak in some way. What's more, because the collective is rooted in a drive for equality, expecting some to put in a labor surplus becomes immoral even if it can be coerced. Conversely, if responsibility rests with the individual there will need to be incentives and pressures to compel individual achievement. These incentives and pressures will create inequality and discomfort. An individualist accepts that as a reality. However, inequality is incompatible with collectivization. Further, discomfort is a form of harm, and the ability to be harmed indicates a weakness, therefore a collectivist will expect discomfort to be alleviated by collective action aimed at protecting the weak. Since the ultimate form of the collective is the government, the collectivists will bring the perspective described above to their political organizations. Meanwhile individualists will do the same when they organize parties opposing collectivization. As a result, "get your house in order" is inescapably political.

While I do agree that individual decision making plays an important role in where a person stands in society, there are significantly larger forces at play that cause one person to end up somewhere in society and what have you (especially in America). Race, socioeconomic status, and even something as simple as where you were born also affect your place in society, just to name a few. For Jordan Peterson to say it's all about individual decision making and to put it so plainly as to 'not make bad life choices', whether intentionally or not he's ignoring not only the sheer amount but also the severity of the other conditions that lead people to be where they are in society. It's also unfortunate that Peterson isn't the only one who believes this. Another person at the forefront of this idea is Ben Shapiro, as he often talks about how the only way to end crime in high-crime areas is for an individual to "decide they're not going to pick up a gun and shoot someone". @Jacob smith Individuals maybe be influenced by others, but all thought is on an individual level. Nobody experiences collective thought. When you vote to make a decision, you aren't relying on the collective knowledge of everyone, but rather the average knowledge. Whenever you make a large group decision, the decision will therefore be inferior to what a well meaning expert would make. That is unless the average person in the group relies on the advice of an expert to cast their vote. Of course there doesn't have to be an absolute hierarchy. There isn't one in any first world country. The governments are based on a system of checks and balances and they don't have absolute rule. Businesses have lots of power, but businesses are competing with other businesses that have their own hierarchies. Then you have other groups and organizations that are neither businesses or governments.

@Jacob smith Everything happens at the individual level. A collective is just a group of individuals. If you want better leadership, then people individually need to choose better on who they follow. If each individual chooses better, we'll collectively choose better and have better leadership. That being said, I think we are too eager to blame leadership for collective problems. If each individual makes poor personal decisions concerning the environment, even if those decisions are small individually, collectively they can have a huge impact. Each individual justifies their own poor choices by blaming leadership.

I consider myself a JBP fan and I can try to explain some of his positions as I understand them. Specifically you ask about the meaning of putting you own house in order, and I'm gonna say what I think about this though I don't claim to understand it completely, I'm still trying to figure this out just like you. To put a house in order should really be taken as a metaphor - though it's also good advice literary. You had a really good question which is who decides if your house is in order and I truly believe that it is your own conscience that decides it. The question is - are you sorted out - by your own standards? People more often than not would say that they are not sorted out - that is - they know they are not 100% doing what they should be doing and they have problems to attend to which they are not attending to. This is something practical - you can try asking this to yourself every night - is there something I should I had done which I didn't or something I wish I hadn't done which I did? If you are still bothered with how you acted during your day this is your conscience telling you that you could have done better. It's a great sign to pay attention to to tell us what we can improve on. So, having said all that, I would define sorting yourself out (or putting your house in order, i see these as analogous metaphors) as the process of solving your personal problems - those that really bother you and you know you can fix - until you reach the point where you are really good at solving problems which concern you primarily. Then you can your family's problems start to become your problem and you are increasingly no longer a problem for your family but a solution to your family's problems and you increasingly take it up yourself to negotiate with them and try to fix the problems. It's crucial to understand that while you don't have yourself sorted out you are more of a problem for someone else, rather than someone who can fix someone else's problem. Why? because you are a problem to yourself - you haven't fixed yourself sufficiently to be of any positive utility to the outer community. Also the meaning of taking responsibilities that goes beyond you as an individual, as I understand it, is that you are turning a problem that is larger than yourself and that other people have into your own *personal* problem - so that you care so much about the problem that you act is if it really concerns you. And then since it concerns, it will also bother your conscience when it's not being attended to and your conscience will impel you to fix it. This is my little rant, trying to articulate these concepts and I hope it can be of a little utility to you James and anyone who cares to read.

It's understandable to be frustrated because you can only do long term improvement, but it's almost a property of life. Change takes time. If you want to become good at something (a sport, an instrument, a scientific area etc.), you have to spend time practicing (a lot). If you want to get rid of some of your bad habits, you'll have to work on them one by one and be constant over time. If you want to improve a relationship, you will have to learn to listen to the other, express your needs clearly, and them come to some compromises and take the time to implement them in real life. If you want to have political power, you have to smart small, improve your network, work on your message and your delivery... There are no shortcuts, and beginning with self-improvement and responsibility is already a step in the good direction. I also think that often, over focusing on large scale problems on which one has no power is a distraction of what can be improved and done on a smaller scale. However I am aware of the tension that exists between Enlightenment thought in general and the historic Biblical understanding of both human nature and history. (I read Voltaire's 'Candide' in college, among other writings of his, also Rousseau's 'Social Contract', both of them before I became a Christian. I can't say that I was favorably impressed.) As Western Christians delve deeper into our Hebraic roots, I think that we find a great chasm opening between two largely incompatible worldviews. But to confuse Christianity with the 'ancien regime' which preceded the French Revolution would be a grave mistake. I believe that the failure of NOMINAL (or 'cultural') Christianity to observe Biblical precepts of justice, also artificially and unnaturally close identification of of Church with State interests, formed the basis for a lot of revolutionary activity and anti-Christian sentiment during the past quarter of a millennium. One must learn to distinguish the doctrine from its perversion by so-called followers. Observe Jesus' parable of the wheat and the tares growing together in a field until harvest time, when they will be separated. I have not seen a single passage in Scripture endorsing 'religion per se', be it 'organized' or 'private'. Have you? Three verses spring to mind: (James 1:26) 'If anyone thinks himself to be religious, yet does not bridle his own tongue but deceives his own heart, this man's religion is worthless.' (James 3:16) 'For where jealousy and selfish ambition exist, there is disorder and every evil thing.' (John 4:23) 'But an hour is coming, and now is, when the true worshipers will worship the Father in spirit and truth; for such people the Father seeks to be His worshipers.'

I'm coming from a kantian perspective rather than a prescriptive religious one, and I consider that to be sufficiently righteous. Define "better". This is a part of the problem, and a bit of the discussion that's usually ignored. Peterson doesn't just mean "make sure there's no trash on the floor" when he says "clean your room". He also means "remove things that don't serve the function of the room" and "order the necessary things to promote the purpose of the room so its purpose can be realized maximally". This requires a deep understanding of what the room is for and what facilitates that and what hinders it. Most people can't even handle keeping the trash off the floor and never get around to deep understanding. And herein lie two problems when we scale up to communal action: firstly, very few have deep understanding of what society *is* and what changes will *actually* produce. Secondly, the few that do often have diametrically opposed values for what "Better" means. Seatbelt enforcement reduces accident fatalities, but it doesn't eliminate them and causes loss of freedom. Is it "better" to be free, or safe? :shrug:
